Constipation, defined by stool consistency and frequency, can be a very common childhood condition that will often lead to fecal incontinence. Dobson (2009) further defines constipation as when a child has experienced two or more of the following characteristics:


less than three bowel movements per week;



more than one episode of fecal incontinence per week;



presence of large stool in the rectum;



production of large stools that obstruct the toilet;



indication in the child’s posture and behavior that stools are being withheld.

Encopresis is the term used when a child, developmentally over 4 years of age, has chronic constipation that leads to involuntary soiling of predominately loose stool. Encopresis occurs in 2.8% of 4 years old, 1.9% of 6 years old, and 1.6% of 10–11 years old (Philichi, 2008). There is some evidence to suggest that there is a relationship between encopresis prevalence and psychiatric problems as well as behavioral and emotional disorders. For example, in a study of children with autism, it was reported that 10–20% of those children had problems with encopresis, and children with bipolar disorder were also found to have higher incidences of fecal soiling (Hardy, 2009). Furthermore, children with emotional and behavioral problems such as attention problems, obsessive and compulsiveness and oppositional behaviors have higher incidences of reported fecal soiling (Hardy, 2009).

The school nurse obtains a child’s complete health history from the parents and the physician and should also request a complete report of the child’s physical examination to develop nursing diagnoses such as knowledge deficit, alteration in elimination, alteration in self-care, and a potential for alteration in self-esteem. Based on these diagnoses, goals are set and interventions are put into place. They may include:


the child and family will gain understanding of the signs and symptoms of constipation and the treatment plan;



the student will demonstrate self-care practices by complying with toileting schedule throughout the day;



the student’s self-esteem will be supported by demonstrating positive feedback and open communication with parents and health care provider.

The school nurse begins the implementation process by developing an individualized health plan (IHP) specific for the child with encopresis (Table 3
). This plan would include an established toileting schedule to allow bathroom breaks in an unhurried, private, and clean environment. It may be part of the health plan that the student comes to the nurse’s office for bathroom breaks several times throughout the school day to allow for the following benefits: cleanliness and privacy of the facility, access to personal care items such as clothing changes, disposable wipes, and bags to store soiled clothing, and allowance for success and failures accurately documented and communicated with the child’s physician and parent.
